{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2df9c37d-74c1-4053-9253-bf013ffdb632","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a scope. In MAUI, **there are no request-based scopes**. The app has a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused forever, causing stale/persisted data.\n\n**Fixes (pick one):**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — a new `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** via `IServiceScopeFactory` when you need request-like lifetime control:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use a DbContext factory** (EF Core's built-in pattern):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject `IDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>` and call `CreateDbContext()` when needed.\n\nOption 3 is generally the recommended approach for MAUI/Blazor/desktop apps.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82f59882-6956-4e59-b357-612b5df04506","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — so `AddScoped` behaves effectively like `AddSingleton`, meaning the same DbContext instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":453,"requestId":"111D:E8763:C541D0:E70C92:69FE883C"},"id":"8daaa558-eed0-4919-ab04-22f9135d388a","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:05:10.621Z","parentId":"ed004c04-97ff-410e-9ce2-21627a451b59"}
